My dear girl-
This is really the first time since christmas as that I could write with any degree of comfort Have been having then natism in my hands and arms. The Dr. pro-nounced it neuralgic. Well this name matters little when one is suffering. I am much better am hoping I am doing the thing now that wil insure a cure. Dear girl I received the lovely lunch cloth and napkins. They are prettier I think than the ones we made. by the way I ahve none and will be so glad to have the one you sent me many thanks dear girl; I surely do appreciate your that of one aside from the beautiful cloth and napkins. He had a very quiet christmas. The children had their tree at home and they 
have eight doz.^eggs to take to market and it is less than a week since I took that many. When you come I'm going to <unclear/> you on chicken and eggs and milk. 
Lulu is getting well we are all so glad about it and she much more I know you had the usual good time at home Remember ^my to your father and mother. How proud Mrs. Preston is of her boy, I had a card from miss Knapp. And her name is on my list of letters to write. I must close now hope you won't <unclear/> so long. My best love to you my little girl and best wishes for the New Year. Alice M. Neihardt 

